713852f-a.text:
119 East 57th Street, north side, east of Park Avenue. The facade of this building was designed by its proprietor, Mr. Todhunter.
About 1925.
Drix Duryea.

722280f-a.text:
Park Avenue, east side, between 57th and 58th Streets, showing Ritz Tower apartment hotel, on N.E. corner of 57th Street, practically completed.

The Building on the N.E. corner of 58th Street is also fairly new, replacing two old garages.

Notice traffic signal tower at 57th Street, of type shortly to be discontinued.

In right background is the Queensboro Bridge at 59th Street, and in the left background, dimly seen, the HellGate Bridge.
1926

Brown Brothers, Photographers.

713857f-a.text:
57th Street, north side, west from Park Avenue. In the centre is the Central Presbyterian Church, which later this same year will be demolished for the erection of the Fuller Building. April 9, 1929.

P.L. Sperr.

713856f-a.text:
57th Street, north side, west from Park Avenue. The tall building in the centre is the new Fuller Building, Madison Avenue at
the N.E. corner of 57th Street.
1930.
Ewing Galloway.

722279f-a.text:
Park Avenue, north from 57th Street, showing faces of buildings on
east side of the avenue.
Note on the N.E. corner of 57th Street the Ritz Tower Apartments (1926) and on S.E. corner of 5wth Street, the old Arion Society
Building (1887).
About 1931.
Ewing Galloway, Photographer.

722278f-a.text:
Park Ave., east side, south from, but not including East 57th Street. Also shown across the sky line, is the R.C.A. Bl4g., the Waldorf Astoria
Hotel and the Grand Central Bldg.
June 11, 1936.
P. L. Sperr.
